Q: Point Inside Polygon or On An Edge A: <p>This code does what you need. You can adapt it to your language:</p>
<pre class="lang-java prettyprint-override"><code>enum TestStageResult   { LEFT, RIGHT, BEYOND, BEHIND, BETWEEN, ORIGIN, DESTINATION }
enum TestEdgeResult    { TOUCHING, CROSSING, INESSENTIAL }
enum TestPolygonResult { INSIDE, OUTSIDE, BOUNDARY }

static TestStageResult classify(Vec2 v0, Vec2 v1, Vec2 v2) {
    Vec2 a = v1.sub(v0);
    Vec2 b = v2.sub(v0);
    float sa = Vec2.cross(a, b); // a.x * b.y - b.x * a.y
    if (sa &gt; 0f) return TestStageResult.LEFT;
    if (sa &lt; 0f) return TestStageResult.RIGHT;
    if (a.x * b.x &lt; 0f || a.y * b.y &lt; 0f) return TestStageResult.BEHIND;
    if (a.lengthSquared() &lt; b.lengthSquared()) return TestStageResult.BEYOND;
    if (isEquals(v0, v2)) return TestStageResult.ORIGIN;
    if (isEquals(v1, v2)) return TestStageResult.DESTINATION;
    return TestStageResult.BETWEEN;
}

static TestEdgeResult edgeType(Vec2 pv, Vec2 pw, Vec2 pa) {
    switch (classify(pv, pw, pa)) {
        case LEFT:
            return pv.y &lt; pa.y &amp;&amp; pa.y &lt;= pw.y
                ? TestEdgeResult.CROSSING
                : TestEdgeResult.INESSENTIAL;
        case RIGHT:
            return pw.y &lt; pa.y &amp;&amp; pa.y &lt;= pv.y
                ? TestEdgeResult.CROSSING
                : TestEdgeResult.INESSENTIAL;
        case BETWEEN:
        case ORIGIN:
        case DESTINATION:
            return TestEdgeResult.TOUCHING;
        default:
            return TestEdgeResult.INESSENTIAL;
    }
}

static TestPolygonResult testPolygon(Vec2 point, Vec2[] points) {
    boolean parity = false;
    for (int i1 = points.length - 1, i2 = 0; i2 &lt; points.length; i1 = i2, ++i2)
        switch (edgeType(points[i1], points[i2], point)) {
            case TOUCHING:
                return TestPolygonResult.BOUNDARY;
            case CROSSING:
                parity = !parity;
        }
    return parity ? TestPolygonResult.INSIDE : TestPolygonResult.OUTSIDE;
}
</code></pre>

Q: R sscanf equivalent A: <p>The POSIX compliant functions <code>sscanf(...)</code> and <code>strptime(...)</code> (<a href="https://www.gnu.org/software/libc/manual/html_node/Formatted-Input-Functions.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">manual page</a>) are format specifier driven, using format specification  to describe the expected sequence of variables, their types and the characters separating these variables (… see example below).</p>
<p>The format string driven concept makes it easy to &quot;define&quot; an expected input format at runtime, while the proposed <code>what = list(...)</code> is &quot;compile time specific&quot;. Therefore, I ask for an equivalent.</p>
<p>Example:</p>
<pre class="lang-c prettyprint-override"><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
#include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
#include &lt;string.h&gt;

int main() {
   char *data = &quot;12 13&quot;;
   char *format = &quot;%d %d %d&quot;;
   int a, b, c;
   int scanned = sscanf(data, format, &amp;a, &amp;b, &amp;c);
   if (scanned != 3) {
     printf(&quot;Cannot scan integer triple '%s' after position %d!\n&quot;,
            data, scanned);
     exit(255);
   }
   exit(0);
}
</code></pre>

Q: How to get records where column is not empty or null in laravel? A: <p>Not sure about the specific laravel version you have, but if it supports scope methods, you can try the following:</p>
<pre><code>// In your SocialIcon model
// added both withLink and withoutLink methods

public function scopeWithLink($query)
{
    return $query-&gt;whereNotNull('link')-&gt;orWhere('link', '&lt;&gt;', '');
}

public function scopeWithoutLink($query)
{
    return $query-&gt;whereNull('link')-&gt;orWhere('link', '');
}
</code></pre>
<p>Then you can use them as chain methods in your model like</p>
<pre><code>// returns SocialIcon where link has value
$socialsWithLink = SocialIcon::withLink()-&gt;get();

// returns SocialIcon where link is either blank or null
$socialsWithoutLink = SocialIcon::withoutLink()-&gt;get();
</code></pre>
